✅ What is the score for node2 in your case?

Your config:

resource 'apachegroup' prefers node 'rocky-node1' with score 100

👉 This means:

node1 → score = +100
node2 → score = 0 (default)
📌 Why node2 = 0?

Because:

You did not define any constraint for node2
So Pacemaker assumes:

👉 “No preference” = score 0

🧠 How cluster compares
Node	Score
rocky-node1	100
rocky-node2	0

✅ Result:

Cluster chooses rocky-node1 because 100 > 0
🔥 Important point

👉 Scores are relative, not absolute.

Node2 is not “bad”
It just has less preference
🧪 What if node1 fails?
node1 unavailable → ignored
node2 (score 0) becomes best available

✅ So apachegroup runs on node2

🔗 With stickiness (your config)

Since you have:

resource-stickiness=INFINITY

If apachegroup is already running on node2:

Node	Score
node1	100
node2	INFINITY

✅ Result:
👉 It stays on node2, even though node1 is preferred

🎯 Final simple answer

👉 In your setup:

node1 score = 100
node2 score = 0 (default)
💡 Tip (very useful in real clusters)

If you want to explicitly set node2:

pcs constraint location apachegroup prefers rocky-node2=50

Then:

Node	Score
node1	100
node2	50

